Throughout set  

\[
M:=n-(s-1)(k-1).\tag{1}
\]

When $M<k$ both sides of $(\star)$ vanish, so we henceforth assume $M\ge k$.

\textbf{Part (a).  Proof of $(\star)$.}  

The argument proceeds through six standard steps.

1. \emph{Compression of the spacing condition.}  
For $S=\{x_{1}<\dots <x_{k}\}$ put  

\[
y_i:=x_i-(i-1)(s-1)\qquad(1\le i\le k).\tag{2}
\]

Since $x_{i+1}-x_i\ge s$, the integers $y_1<\dots <y_k$ form an ordinary $k$-subset of $\{1,\dots ,M\}$, and \eqref{2} is a bijection.

2. \emph{Translation of the congruence.}  
Summing \eqref{2} gives  

\[
\sum_{i=1}^{k}x_i=\sum_{i=1}^{k}y_i+(s-1)\frac{k(k-1)}{2},\tag{3}
\]
so  

\[
\sum_{i=1}^{k}y_i\equiv r-\frac{(s-1)k(k-1)}{2}\pmod q.\tag{4}
\]
Write  

\[
c\equiv r-\frac{(s-1)k(k-1)}{2}\pmod q.\tag{5}
\]

We thus count $k$-subsets of $\{1,\dots ,M\}$ whose element-sum is congruent to $c$ modulo $q$.

3. \emph{A bivariate generating series.}  
Introduce indeterminates $u$ (subset size) and $z$ (element sum) and define  

\[
F(u,z):=\prod_{j=1}^{M}\bigl(1+u\,z^{\,j}\bigr).\tag{6}
\]

The coefficient of $u^{k}z^{m}$ in $F$ counts the desired subsets with sum $m$.

4. \emph{Root-of-unity filter.}  
With $\omega=e^{2\pi i/q}$ we project onto $m\equiv c\pmod q$:

\[
A_{n,k}^{(s,q,r)}
=\frac1q\sum_{t=0}^{q-1}\omega^{-tc}\,\bigl[u^{k}\bigr]F\!\bigl(u,z=\omega^{t}\bigr).\tag{7}
\]

5. \emph{Extraction of the $u^{k}$-coefficient.}  
Fix $t$ and abbreviate $\xi:=\omega^{t}$, $v:=u\xi$.  Gauss' $q$-binomial theorem yields  

\[
\prod_{j=0}^{M-1}(1+v\,\xi^{\,j})
     =\sum_{\ell=0}^{M}v^{\ell}\xi^{\,\ell(\ell-1)/2}
       \bigl[{M\choose \ell}\bigr]_{\xi}.\tag{8}
\]

Replacing $v$ by $u\xi$ and extracting $u^{k}$ we get  

\[
\bigl[u^{k}\bigr]F(u,\xi)=\xi^{\,k(k+1)/2}\,
                           \bigl[{M\choose k}\bigr]_{\xi}.\tag{9}
\]

6. \emph{Assembly.}  Insert \eqref{9} into \eqref{7} and recall \eqref{5}:

\[
\begin{aligned}
A_{n,k}^{(s,q,r)}
&=\frac1q\sum_{t=0}^{q-1}
   \omega^{-tc}\,
   \omega^{\,t\,k(k+1)/2}\,
   \bigl[{M\choose k}\bigr]_{\omega^{t}} \\[4pt]
&=\frac1q\sum_{t=0}^{q-1}
   \omega^{-tr}\,
   \omega^{\,t\,(s-1)k(k-1)/2}\,
   \omega^{\,t\,k(k+1)/2}\,
   \bigl[{M\choose k}\bigr]_{\omega^{t}},
\end{aligned}
\]

which is precisely $(\star)$.  Part (a) is complete.

\bigskip
\textbf{Part (b).  Specialisations.}

\smallskip
\textbf{(i)  Modulus $q=2$.}  
Now $\omega=-1$ and $t\in\{0,1\}$.  Put  

\[
E:=-r+\frac{(s-1)k(k-1)}{2}+\frac{k(k+1)}{2}.\tag{10}
\]

Formula $(\star)$ gives  

\[
A_{n,k}^{(s,2,r)}
=\frac12\,\binom{M}{k}
+\frac12\,(-1)^{E}\,
          \bigl[{M\choose k}\bigr]_{-1}.\tag{11}
\]

The classical evaluation  

\[
\bigl[{M\choose k}\bigr]_{-1}
=\begin{cases}
0, & k(M-k)\text{ odd},\\[8pt]
\displaystyle\binom{\lfloor M/2\rfloor}{\lfloor k/2\rfloor}, & k(M-k)\text{ even},
\end{cases}\tag{12}
\]

turns \eqref{11} into a fully explicit closed form.

\smallskip
\textbf{(ii)  Separation $s=2$ and \emph{prime} modulus $q$.}  

Here $M=n-k+1=:N$, so $(\star)$ reads  

\[
A_{n,k}^{(2,q,r)}
=\frac1q\sum_{t=0}^{q-1}
  \omega^{\,t\,(k^{2}-r)}\,
  \bigl[{N\choose k}\bigr]_{\omega^{t}}.\tag{13}
\]

\emph{Separating the contribution $t=0$.}  Since $\omega^{0}=1$,  

\[
\bigl[{N\choose k}\bigr]_{1}=\binom{N}{k},
\]
whence  

\[
A_{n,k}^{(2,q,r)}
=\frac{1}{q}\binom{N}{k}
+\frac{1}{q}\sum_{t=1}^{q-1}
  \omega^{\,t\,(k^{2}-r)}\,
  \bigl[{N\choose k}\bigr]_{\omega^{t}}.\tag{14}
\]

\emph{$q$-Lucas decomposition for $t\neq0$.}  
Because $q$ is prime, every $\omega^{t}$ ($t=1,\dots ,q-1$) is a primitive $q$-th root; hence $\omega^{t\,j}\neq1$ for $1\le j\le q-1$.  Write  

\[
N=qM_{1}+M_{0},\qquad 
k=qk_{1}+k_{0},\qquad 0\le M_{0},k_{0}<q.\tag{15}
\]

$q$-Lucas' theorem gives  

\[
\bigl[{N\choose k}\bigr]_{\omega^{t}}
=\binom{M_{1}}{k_{1}}\,
 \bigl[{M_{0}\choose k_{0}}\bigr]_{\omega^{t}}.\tag{16}
\]

\emph{Evaluating the small Gaussian coefficient.}  
Because $M_{0},k_{0}<q$ and $\omega^{t\,j}\neq1$ for $1\le j\le q-1$,  

\[
\bigl[{M_{0}\choose k_{0}}\bigr]_{\omega^{t}}
=\begin{cases}
0, & k_{0}>M_{0},\\[10pt]
\displaystyle\prod_{j=1}^{k_{0}}
     \frac{1-\omega^{t\,(M_{0}-k_{0}+j)}}{1-\omega^{t\,j}},
 & k_{0}\le M_{0}.
\end{cases}\tag{17}
\]

All denominators are non-zero, so \eqref{17} is well defined.

\emph{Putting everything together.}  Substituting \eqref{16}-\eqref{17} into \eqref{14} yields  

\[
\boxed{\;
A_{n,k}^{(2,q,r)}=
\frac{1}{q}\binom{n-k+1}{k}\;+\;
\frac{\binom{M_{1}}{k_{1}}}{q}\,
\mathbf 1_{\,k_{0}\le M_{0}}\,
\sum_{t=1}^{q-1}\omega^{\,t\,(k^{2}-r)}
\prod_{j=1}^{k_{0}}
     \frac{1-\omega^{t\,(M_{0}-k_{0}+j)}}{1-\omega^{t\,j}}
}\tag{18}
\]

where $\mathbf 1_{\,\ast}$ is the indicator ($1$ if the condition holds, $0$ otherwise).  
Formula \eqref{18} expresses $A_{n,k}^{(2,q,r)}$ as a finite sum of $(q-1)$ explicit products, each involving at most $2k_{0}$ ordinary complex numbers, and is therefore a bona-fide closed form.

\smallskip
\textbf{Two immediate corollaries.}

1.  \emph{The case $k\equiv 0\pmod q$ (hence $k_{0}=0$).}  
Now the empty product equals $1$, and

\[
\sum_{t=1}^{q-1}\omega^{\,t\,(k^{2}-r)}
=
\begin{cases}
q-1,& k^{2}\equiv r\pmod q,\\
-1,& k^{2}\not\equiv r\pmod q.
\end{cases}
\]

Hence \eqref{18} gives  

\[
A_{n,k}^{(2,q,r)}
=
\begin{cases}
\displaystyle
\binom{M_{1}}{k_{1}}
+\dfrac1q\Bigl(\binom{N}{k}-\binom{M_{1}}{k_{1}}\Bigr), & k^{2}\equiv r\pmod q,\\[10pt]
\displaystyle
\dfrac1q\Bigl(\binom{N}{k}-\binom{M_{1}}{k_{1}}\Bigr), & k^{2}\not\equiv r\pmod q.
\end{cases}\tag{19}
\]

This corrects the erroneous omission of the additional term $\dfrac1q\bigl(\binom{N}{k}-\binom{M_{1}}{k_{1}}\bigr)$ in the original draft.

2.  \emph{Compatibility with $q=2$.}  
Specialising \eqref{18} to $q=2$ gives precisely \eqref{11}-\eqref{12}, so formula \eqref{18} is consistent with part (i).

\bigskip
The argument is complete.
